<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
Being a lost soul should become an option rather than a subrace in my opinion, after all I'm sure barbarians and hermits can also go into Mandos, though undeads should not be able to. <p>
<strong><a href="./FuriousOne">FuriousOne</a></strong>: Barbarians and hermits can go to the halls of Mandos, but if they're human, they cannot come back. Elves, Men, and Dwarves all go to the halls of waiting. It is only Elves, however, who are ever allowed to come back from the Halls to walk on Arda. So ToME already allows way too many races to find themselves in the Halls that never should be able to, thematically. :P 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NerdanelVampire">NerdanelVampire</a>: Well, it seems to me that no game-style Lost Souls are actually allowed to leave, as the inhabitants of the Halls keep fighting them. It seems to me the ToME Lost Souls are souls who accepted the call to go to Mandos, but once in it, they got second thoughts and decided to break free against the wishes of the Valar. Even Lost Soul Orcs and such can work, as it is very reasonable that they go SOMEWHERE after their death. 
</p>
<p>
I'd like to think Glorfindel didn't need to engage in stairscumming and the killing of dragonflies, but that Mandos got him out and embodied without a hassle. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./FuriousOne">FuriousOne</a></strong>: Orcs and trolls upon Valinor? I don't think that's very likely. o.O In fact, the whole name 'Halls of Mandos' should probably be scrapped for a more generic Halls of Waiting, because I agree that even orcs must go somewhere after death. But that somewhere is almost certainly not Valinor. And to think that Mandos would allow dreads and dragons in his house, not to mention orcs... I strongly doubt it. *makes a note to change the Mandos dungeon name in Theme and remove elf-y restrictions* 
</p>
<p>
Simon: So if I get killed in the halls of Mandos, where do I end up? (-; 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NerdanelVampire">NerdanelVampire</a>: I've always liked to imagine you are just returned to your rightful place of waiting and you can try to escape again. My Lost Souls certainly do that a lot. One hobbit sorceror did over 120 tries, "dying" quickly in most cases. Only in a very late case did I find a potion of self-knowledge and learn that her luck had somehow been negative(!) all along... And that was with a hobbit! I stopped trying about that point, as the Roman numbering was also getting cumbersome. 
</p>
